       two cities is up to 20 degrees centigrade. Due to door openings;
       product removal/loading; conduction through walls, roofs, and
       floors of the refrigerated warehouses and vehicles; and length of
       the journey; the heat transfer between the outside air and
       refrigerators is highly affected by the outdoor air temperatures
       [4][5][6][7]. Consequently, the outdoor ambient temperature
       conditions during transportation and storage will change the energy
       consumption for maintaining the set-point temperature. It will
       impact the GHG (greenhouse gas) emission and, consequently, affect
       the design of green cold chains delicately. ...
       ... The carbon emissions of DCs in the cold chain are generated
       when maintaining refrigerated warehouses where the products are
       stored, removed, and loaded. Due to door openings; product
       removal/loading; and the heat conduction through doors, walls,
       roofs, and floors; the emission rate is positively correlated with
       the outdoor ambient temperature [4,6]. Consequently, the location
       of the DCs will affect the outdoor ambient temperature patterns, as
       well as the energy use and emissions, accordingly. ...
