     * Sustainable Food Supply Chain Design
       Chapter
          + Jan 2017
          + M. Soysal
            M. Soysal
          + Jacqueline Bloemhof-Ruwaard
            Jacqueline Bloemhof-Ruwaard
       Supply Chain Management (SCM) has become part of the c-management
       agenda in Western countries since the 1990s, particularly in the
       manufacturing and retail industries (Chopra and Meindl 2012). More
       recently, interest in SCM has also been growing in the agrifood
       industry, both in developed and developing countries. Executives of
       agrifood companies are aware that successful coordination,
       integration, and management of key business processes in the supply
       chain will determine their competitive success. Sustainable Food
       Supply Chain Management (SFSCM) refers to all forward processes in
       the food chain, like procurement of materials, production and
       distribution, as well as the reverse processes to collect and
       process returned used or unused products and/or parts of products
       in order to ensure a socioeconomically and ecologically sustainable
       recovery (Bloemhof and van Nunen 2008).
