       (BUTTON) Show abstract
     * The food cold-chain and climate change
       Article
          + Aug 2010
          + FOOD RES INT
          + Stephen John James
            Stephen John James
          + Christian James
            Christian James
       Any noticeable increase in ambient temperature resulting from
       climatic change will have a substantial effect on the current and
       developing food cold-chain. A rise in temperature will increase the
       risk of food poisoning and food spoilage unless the cold-chain is
       extended and improved. The little data that is available suggests
       that currently the cold-chain accounts for approximately 1% of CO2
       production in the world, however this is likely to increase if
       global temperatures increase significantly. Using the most energy
       efficient refrigeration technologies it would be possible to
       substantially extend and improve the cold-chain without any
       increase in CO2, and possibly even a decrease.
